{
  "texts": [
    "The LDM, expecting a meaningful distribution in the latent space, fails to generate coherent outputs from this degenerate input.",
    "This collapse represents a total loss of information about the original data variability, matching the Objective 2, which makes it impossible for the LDM to recover meaningful features or structures.",
    "D. Optimization FrameworkTo craft adversarial samples, we use projected sign gradient ascent [21] for iterative updates.",
    "Our approach is inspired by a counterintuitive finding from [8]: they achieved better results by minimizing their loss function, which contradicts the intuitive expectation that maximization would be moreAlgorithm 1 Posterior Collapse Attack (PCA) Require: Clean image x, VAE encoder E, perturbation budget ϵ, step size α, number of iterations T, variance parameter v, objective type obj ∈ {+, -} Ensure: Adversarial image x adv 1: Initialize: x 0 ← x, δ 0 ← 0 2: for t = 1 to T do 3: // Forward pass through VAE encoder 4: µ t, σ t ← E(x t-1) 5:// Compute the loss (in Equation 12)6:L KL (x t-1) = 1 2 d i=1 -ln(σ t i) 2 -1 + (µ t i) 2 +(σ t i) 2 v 7:// Compute gradient 8:g t ← ∇ x t-1 L KL (x t-1) 9:if obj = + then 10:// Maximize for diffusion collapse (PCA+) 11:δ t ← δ t-1 + α • sign(g t) 12:else if obj =then 13:// Minimize for concentration collapse (PCA-) 14:δ t ← δ t-1 -α • sign(g t) 15: end if 16:// Project perturbation into ℓ ∞ ball 17:δ t ← clip(δ t, -ϵ, ϵ) 18:// Update adversarial image 19:x t ← clip(x + δ t, 0, 1) 20: end for 21: x adv ← x T 22: return x adv effective.",
    "Following this insight, we explore both gradient directions by altering the sign of our final loss function, which will be discussed in appendix."
  ]
}